		<bioghist encodinganalog="545">
			<head>Biographical History</head>
			<p>Associated American Artists is an art gallery and business established in 1934 in New York City by Reeves Lewenthal.  It focused on popularizing and marketing fine art prints to the middle classes.</p>
		</bioghist>

		<scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
			<head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
			<p>Clippings, exhibition catalogs, and photographs pertaining to the organization's history and to specific artists including Howard Baer (1941-1946); Thomas Hart Benton (1939-1946); Arbit Blatas (1943-1951); Aaron Bohrod (1939-1942); John Steuart Curry (1942-1947); Adolf Dehn (1941-1948); George Grosz (1941-1950); Joe Jones (1942-1948); Luigi Lucioni (1939-1951); Grant Wood (1935-1950), and others.</p>
		</scopecontent>
		
		<arrangement encodinganalog="351$a">
			<head>Arrangement of the Collection</head>
			<p><emph render="bold">Artists</emph> contains material relating to Howard Baer, Thomas Hart Benton, Arbit Blatas, 
			Aaron Bohrod, John Steuart Curry, Adolf Dehn, George Grosz, Joe Jones, Luigi Lucioni, and Grant 
			Wood.</p>
			<p>Clippings and exhibition catalogs document the Association's <emph render="bold">History - General</emph>, including print sales and Stonelain Pottery projects, client promotions for American Tobacco Company, 
			Lowenstein, Ohrbachs, and Riverdale as well as promotional material for the gallery.</p><p><emph render="bold">Catalogs</emph> contains catalogs for prints, etchings, lithographs, and gifts spanning nearly forty years, including sale catalogs, Patrons Supplements, Print Collector newslettter/catalog, and catalogs features individual artists.</p>
		</arrangement>
		
